# https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Accuracy captures the degree to which a dataset correctly and precisely represents information, in accordance with defined standards."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalAccuracy> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#precision> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#semanticAccuracy> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#syntacticAccuracy> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Accuracy"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#appropriateness
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#appropriateness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#appropriateness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#appropriateness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#understandability> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#appropriateness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Appropriateness refers to the ease with which data can be understood without ambiguity within a given context of use."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#appropriateness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "The city name 'London' as a birthplace may be ambiguous and can lead to misunderstandings, as there are multiple cities with that name in different countries. Providing geolocations or references to a location register reduces ambiguity and increase understanding."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#appropriateness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Appropriateness"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#appropriateness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#appropriateness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.3233/SW-150175> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#appropriateness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.dama-nl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/3DQ-Dictionary-of-Dimensions-of-Data-Quality-version-1.2-d.d.-14-Nov-2020.pdf> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#appropriateness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.iso.org/standard/35736.html> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#availability
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#availability> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#availability> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#availability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#accessibility> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#availability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Availability is the degree to which data can be accessed when required for a given context of use."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#availability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Accessing a resource through a website enhances its availability. Specifying a unique and persistent identifier, such as a Digital Object Identifier (DOI), further improves availability by ensuring that an organization is responsible for maintaining the resource's integrity and long-term accessibility."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#availability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Availability"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#availability> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#availability> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.3233/SW-150175> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#availability> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.dama-nl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/3DQ-Dictionary-of-Dimensions-of-Data-Quality-version-1.2-d.d.-14-Nov-2020.pdf> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#availability> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://doi.org/10.1145/240455.240479> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#availability> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://www.iso.org/standard/35736.html> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#causalTraceability
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#causalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#causalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#causalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#traceability> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#causalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Causal Traceability is the degree to which causal dependencies among dataset updates are documented and accessible for a given context of use."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#causalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Changes to a historic building may trigger updates to related data, such as the group of architects responsible for modifications of the building. In this context, sculptures may have been relocated due to change."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#causalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Causal Traceability"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#causalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#causalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://doi.org/10.1145/3362121> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#consistency> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Coherence refers to the degree to which the dataset contains coherent data elements. Two data elements are coherent if their respective properties and links are coherent in pairs. Two properties are coherent if their data values are the same when representing the same information. Two links are coherent if they refer to the same element when representing the same information. Two data values are coherent if similar information is expressed in a consistent format."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Each city should be represented by a single data element, ensuring that all links to that city are unambiguous."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "In a dataset of photograph metadata, all elements are coherent if measurements for width and height are specified consistently across records."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Location name London must be unambiguous for cities; This can be achieved, e.g., by a suffix such as London (United Kingdom)."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Measurement values are coherent if their formats are identical. For example, integers should be consistently represented without leading zeros."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Width and height values should use the same units, such as cm, for all elements."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Coherence"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.3233/SW-150175> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.dama-nl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/3DQ-Dictionary-of-Dimensions-of-Data-Quality-version-1.2-d.d.-14-Nov-2020.pdf> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.iso.org/standard/35736.html> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://doi.org/10.1145/1012453.1012461> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://doi.org/10.1145/1541880.1541883> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://doi.org/10.1145/240455.240479> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#conciseness> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Compactness refers to the degree to which a dataset contains no redundant elements and all elements are compact. A data element is compact if it does not contain redundant links or properties. A data value is compact if it is as condensed as possible."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "A data element that specifies the size of a photograph is compact if it includes only the relevant measurement (e.g., the size of photograph itself) without redundant information (e.g., the frame size, unless contextually required)."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "A data value for the width of a photograph is compact if it is expressed in a concise numeric form, without unnecessary leading zeros."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "A dataset of paintings from an exhibition is compact if it does not contain multiple elements describing the same painting."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Compactness"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.iso.org/standard/35736.html> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://www.dama-nl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/3DQ-Dictionary-of-Dimensions-of-Data-Quality-version-1.2-d.d.-14-Nov-2020.pdf> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasInfluencedBy> <https://doi.org/10.3233/SW-150175> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#completeness
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#completeness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#completeness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#completeness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Completeness refers to the extent to which all information required for a particular context of use is present."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#completeness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalCompleteness> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#completeness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#completeness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Completeness"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#completeness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Compliance refers to the degree to which the dataset conforms to rules and guidelines established for the employed data description language and, where applicable, the associated data model."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "The guidelines for recording cultural heritage data may require photographs' dimensions to be given in cm."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "The internationally recognized ISO 8601 standard prescribes the date format YYYY-MM-DD."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Compliance"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.dama-nl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/3DQ-Dictionary-of-Dimensions-of-Data-Quality-version-1.2-d.d.-14-Nov-2020.pdf> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.iso.org/standard/35736.html> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://doi.org/10.1145/1012453.1012461> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#compliance> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://doi.org/10.3233/SW-150175> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#conciseness
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#conciseness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#conciseness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#conciseness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Conciseness reflects the degree to which a dataset presents essential information efficiently."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#conciseness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#compactness> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#conciseness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#relevance> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#conciseness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Conciseness"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#conciseness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#confidentiality
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#confidentiality> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#confidentiality> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#confidentiality> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#accessibility> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#confidentiality> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Confidentiality refers to the restriction of access to authorized users only, ensuring that sensitive data is protected according to the requirements of a given context of use."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#confidentiality> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Certain information, such as the owner's name of an object form, may be crucial for provenance tracking in a museum but must be hidden during data export to protect privacy."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#confidentiality> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Role-based access control is often applied to data collections. For example, new staff may be permitted to edit newly entered data, whereas editors have write access to all the data within a collection."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#confidentiality> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Confidentiality"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#confidentiality> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#confidentiality> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.dama-nl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/3DQ-Dictionary-of-Dimensions-of-Data-Quality-version-1.2-d.d.-14-Nov-2020.pdf> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#confidentiality> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.iso.org/standard/35736.html> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#confidentiality> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://doi.org/10.3233/SW-150175> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#consistency
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#consistency> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#consistency> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#consistency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Consistency refers to the uniformity of information within a dataset without internal conflicts."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#consistency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#coherence> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#consistency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#logicalConsistency> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#consistency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Consistency"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#consistency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Category> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Contextual Dimensions"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#currency
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#currency> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#currency> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#currency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Currency refers to the extent to which a dataset reflects up-to-date information from the domain of interest."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#currency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataCurrency> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#currency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataUpdateCurrency> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#currency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#timeConcurrency> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#currency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Currency"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#currency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataCurrency
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#currency> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Data Currency refers to the degree to which a dataset contains up-to-date information relevant to the domain of interest."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Paintings can change ownership at auctions. To accurately determine the current location of an artist's paintings, the data must always be up-to-date."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Data Currency"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.3233/SW-150175> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.dama-nl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/3DQ-Dictionary-of-Dimensions-of-Data-Quality-version-1.2-d.d.-14-Nov-2020.pdf> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.iso.org/standard/35736.html> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataUpdateCurrency
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataUpdateCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataUpdateCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataUpdateCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#currency> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataUpdateCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Data Update Currency refers to the degree to which a dataset is updated promptly after information in a domain of interest has changed."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataUpdateCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Museum inventories are conducted periodically and may reveal discrepancies with existing data. The closer an inventory is performed relative to changes in holdings, the more current the data."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataUpdateCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Natural dynamics, such as the tilt of the Leaning Tower of Pisa, are monitored regularly. The more recent the measurements, the more accurately the data reflects the current state."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataUpdateCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Data Update Currency"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataUpdateCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataUpdateCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.1145/1012453.1012461> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#dataUpdateCurrency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.1145/240455.240479> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalAccuracy
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "External Accuracy refers to the degree to which all interlinks in a dataset are valid and refer to the intended data elements in external datasets."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "A link to an artwork type is accurate if the type is as specific as possible. Typical registers such as the controlled vocabulary Art & Architecture Thesaurus (AAT) capture multidimensional relationships and provide links to general and more specific entries."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "A place of birth may be indicated by a name, which should ideally be accompanied by a link to a location register. For external accuracy, this link must be valid and resolvable."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "External Accuracy"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://doi.org/10.3233/SW-150175> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasInfluencedBy> <https://www.dama-nl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/3DQ-Dictionary-of-Dimensions-of-Data-Quality-version-1.2-d.d.-14-Nov-2020.pdf> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalCompleteness
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#completeness> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "External Completeness refers to the degree to which a dataset contains all interlinks to external datasets that are required for a particular context of use."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "To avoid ambiguity, each place of birth should be indicated by a valid link to a specific location register, such as GeoNames."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "External Completeness"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.3233/SW-150175> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasInfluencedBy> <https://www.dama-nl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/3DQ-Dictionary-of-Dimensions-of-Data-Quality-version-1.2-d.d.-14-Nov-2020.pdf> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#externalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasInfluencedBy> <https://www.iso.org/standard/35736.html> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#integrity
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#integrity> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#integrity> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#integrity> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#accessibility> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#integrity> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Integrity refers to the degree to which data remains free from unintentional or unauthorized alterations, preserving its intended state over time."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#integrity> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Techniques such as digital signatures and cryptographic hashes can be employed to verify the authenticity of data changes, thereby distinguishing authorized changes from unauthorized or accidental alterations."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#integrity> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Integrity"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#integrity> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#integrity> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.dama-nl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/3DQ-Dictionary-of-Dimensions-of-Data-Quality-version-1.2-d.d.-14-Nov-2020.pdf> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#integrity> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://doi.org/10.1145/3362121> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#integrity> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://doi.org/10.3233/SW-150175> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#integrity> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://www.iso.org/standard/35736.html> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#completeness> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Internal Completeness refers to the degree to which a dataset contains all data elements of the domain of interest required for a particular context of use, and each of those data elements includes the properties and links required for the intended context of use."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "In a register of paintings, all paintings created by a particular artist must be included to create a chronological overview of the artist's work."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "To determine the century in which a person lived, the year of birth may be sufficient. However, assigning a zodiac sign or software-based verification to disambiguating persons with the identical names typically requires the full date of birth."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Internal Completeness"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.1145/1012453.1012461> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.1145/1541880.1541883> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.1145/240455.240479> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.3233/SW-150175> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.dama-nl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/3DQ-Dictionary-of-Dimensions-of-Data-Quality-version-1.2-d.d.-14-Nov-2020.pdf> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#internalCompleteness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.iso.org/standard/35736.html> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Category> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Intrinsic Dimensions"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#logicalConsistency
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#logicalConsistency> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#logicalConsistency> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#logicalConsistency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#consistency> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#logicalConsistency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Logical Consistency refers to the degree to which a dataset is free from logical contradictions within a given domain of interest and context of use."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#logicalConsistency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "The date of a person's death must not precede their date of birth; any violation constitutes a logical contradiction."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#logicalConsistency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Logical Consistency"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#logicalConsistency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#logicalConsistency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.1145/1541880.1541883> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#logicalConsistency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.3233/SW-150175> .
