# https://w3id.org/dqvch#semanticAccuracy
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#semanticAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#semanticAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#semanticAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#accuracy> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#semanticAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Semantic Accuracy refers to the degree to which the dataset correctly represents information of the domain of interest."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#semanticAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "If a building can be attributed with a date, it depends on the description in the data model what kind of date it is. For instance, recording the foundation date of a church when the model specifies the completion date would be semantically inaccurate."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#semanticAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "The Mona Lisa is a painting by Leonardo da Vinci. Attributing the painting to the artist Pablo Picasso would be semantically inaccurate."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#semanticAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Semantic Accuracy"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#semanticAccuracy> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#intrinsicDimensions> .
