# https://w3id.org/dqvch#temporalTraceability
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#temporalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#temporalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#temporalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#traceability> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#temporalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Temporal Traceability is the degree to which a dataset has an audit trail of access and a history of changes within a particular context of use."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#temporalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Historic buildings are typically dynamic in nature. All changes, additions, and demolitions to a building should be recorded in a detailed history of change to maintain temporal traceability."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#temporalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Temporal Traceability"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#temporalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#temporalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.iso.org/standard/35736.html> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#temporalTraceability> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <https://www.dama-nl.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/3DQ-Dictionary-of-Dimensions-of-Data-Quality-version-1.2-d.d.-14-Nov-2020.pdf> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/dqvch#timeConcurrency
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#timeConcurrency> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#timeConcurrency> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#timeConcurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#currency> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#timeConcurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Time Concurrency assesses whether all data elements, including their values and links, refer consistently to the same version of information in the domain."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#timeConcurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "In a museum, paintings may be relocated as part of an exhibition. If some paintings' location data are already updated to the current exhibition, while others remain outdated, the data lacks time concurrency, resulting in inconsistent representation of the exhibition."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#timeConcurrency> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Time Concurrency"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#timeConcurrency> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> .
