# https://w3id.org/dqvch#trustworthiness
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#trustworthiness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#trustworthiness> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#trustworthiness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#plausibility> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#trustworthiness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Trustworthiness refers to the degree to which a dataset, including its elements and values, are believed by a relevant community within a specific context of use."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#trustworthiness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Cultural heritage information published by a reputable museum about an object in its possession is generally more trustworthy than information in tourist promotional material, as the museum is recognized for its expertise and responsible handling of information."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#trustworthiness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Similarly, the reputation, education, and experience of the data contributor influence trustworthiness."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#trustworthiness> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Trustworthiness"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#trustworthiness> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> .
