# https://w3id.org/dqvch#versatility
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#versatility> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#versatility> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#Dimension> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#versatility> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#understandability> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#versatility> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "Versatility refers to the extent to which data is available in different forms across different cultural perspectives, technology platforms, and user sensory abilities."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#versatility> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Historical dates prior to 1582 require distinguishing between the Julian and Gregorian calendars. Providing data in multiple formats or adhering to ISO 8601 can prevent misinterpretation and enhance versatility."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#versatility> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "Measurements in the metric system are easily understood in Europe but may be less intuitive for US Americans."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#versatility> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example> "The date of New Year's celebration varies between the Gregorian and lunar calendars, necessitating contextual clarification."@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#versatility> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Versatility"@en .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#versatility> <http://www.w3.org/ns/dqv#inCategory> <https://w3id.org/dqvch#contextualDimensions> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#versatility> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://doi.org/10.1145/3362121> .
<https://w3id.org/dqvch#versatility> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#hadPrimarySource> <https://www.iso.org/standard/35736.html> .
